Three operating modes

The NSB should formally support three modes.

Mode I — Asset Synthesis Bridge

The neural system produces actual world assets.

Use when:
	•	new buildings
	•	props
	•	characters
	•	terrain chunks

Pipeline:

Semantic intent
→ latent generation
→ mesh/material/collider synthesis
→ scene insertion

Best for persistent objects.

Strength

Stable and reusable.

Weakness

More expensive and slower.

⸻

Mode II — Neural Overlay Bridge

The runtime holds coarse geometry; neural systems supply appearance.

Use when:
	•	atmosphere
	•	local detail
	•	style shifts
	•	non-critical visual richness
	•	cinematic enhancement

Pipeline:

Runtime geometry
→ neural visual enhancement
→ final frame output

Best for perceptual fidelity without destabilizing simulation.

Strength

Fast, flexible, beautiful.

Weakness

Can drift if unconstrained.

⸻

Mode III — Hybrid Bridge

The default and most realistic architecture.

Persistent, interactable objects become explicit spatial entities.
High-frequency or stylistic detail stays neural.

Pipeline:

Stable structure → explicit runtime object
Dynamic richness → neural overlay

Examples:
	•	castle walls = explicit mesh/collision/nav
	•	moss, cracks, fog, dramatic lighting = neural enhancement

This is likely the canonical IWDS mode.

