Translation principle

The NSB should be governed by a formal translation law:

Translation Invariant

A world-object is successfully bridged when its load-bearing meaning survives conversion across substrates.

That means translation is judged by invariants, not appearance alone.

Example: “castle”

Load-bearing invariants may include:
	•	defensible elevated structure
	•	stone/fortified character
	•	interior/exterior distinction
	•	traversability
	•	landmark salience

These can survive across:
	•	text
	•	latent
	•	mesh
	•	render
	•	stylization

But if the output looks pretty and loses defensibility or traversability, the bridge failed.

So the NSB does not ask:
“Does it resemble a castle visually?”

It asks:
“Did the castle-pattern survive operationally?”

